<dl id="n08079f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08079f">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08079f"> 79(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> alaki = to feel a camel&apos;s hump 3 / times with the right hand to / find out whether it is / fit to carry a load of 20 / stone (Ar)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A language has always many terms for those things that interest the speakers in their daily doings; thus Sweet says: &lsquo;if we open an Arabic dictionary at random, we may expect to find something about a camel: &lsquo;a young camel&rsquo;, &lsquo;an old camel&rsquo; &hellip; &lsquo;to feel a camel&apos;s hump to ascertain its fatness&rsquo; &hellip; <font color="green">[n1: Sweet, <cite>The Practical Study of Language</cite>, 1899, p.163.]</font> <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 52</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02234e" href="c02all.htm#c02234e">VI.C.02:234(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
